1. Architecture & UX
Suggestion	Detailed Description
Async Job + Polling	The generation pipeline runs in a background thread using Spring's @Async. The frontend receives a jobId immediately and polls a status endpoint every 1.5 seconds. The status response includes: current stage name (e.g., "Assessing complexity"), a progress percentage, an elapsed time counter, and when complete, the final result. This turns a 90-second black-box wait into a transparent, reassuring progress display. No WebSockets or Server-Sent Events required—plain HTTP polling keeps it simple.
Parallel Module Expansion	Instead of expanding modules one by one (Module 1 → wait 30s → Module 2 → wait 30s → ...), all modules are expanded concurrently using CompletableFuture.allOf(). This means if you have 6 modules and each takes 30 seconds, total time drops from 180 seconds to ~30 seconds (the time of the slowest single module). The system limits concurrency to avoid rate-limiting all providers at once (e.g., max 4 parallel calls).
Progressive (JIT) Generation	The Outline is returned to the user as soon as it's generated (~90 seconds). While the user reads and edits the outline, Module 1's details are generated in the background. Modules 3–6 are deferred entirely—they only generate when the user finishes Module 2. This "just-in-time" approach prevents wasting AI quota on content the user may never reach, and gets something useful in their hands as fast as possible.
Tiered Quality Fast-Fallback	For each AI call, the system tries providers in sequence with specific timeouts: Groq (5 seconds) → Gemini (15 seconds) → NVIDIA (45 seconds). If all three fail or time out, the system returns a "Skeleton" response—a structure with module titles and step placeholders, but no detailed content. A background task then attempts to fill in the missing details. This ensures the user always gets something useful, even during provider outages.
2. Core Generation Logic
Suggestion	Detailed Description
Archetype Categorization	The Assessment pass now classifies every goal into one of four archetypes: MICRO_TASK (e.g., "Read Chapter 3"), TOPIC_DEEP_DIVE (e.g., "Master Docker"), CERTIFICATION_PREP (e.g., "Pass AWS Exam"), or CAREER_PIVOT (e.g., "Become a DevOps Engineer"). This classification drives everything downstream—structure, depth, resource density, and even the AI's persona. A "read a book chapter" roadmap is treated as a quick task, while a career path gets a multi-phase, project-heavy structure.
Phase-Based Structure (Career Paths)	For CAREER_PIVOT roadmaps, the AI is forced to generate a 4-phase structure: Foundations (core concepts, prerequisites), Core Tooling (the main technologies), Specialization (advanced/deep topics), and Portfolio/Capstone (real-world projects to showcase). Each phase has its own progress bar, and the user sees their advancement through these phases, not just through individual steps. This mirrors how real career transitions actually work.
Project Portfolio Mandate	For career paths, every module after the Foundations phase must end with a concrete, publicly-shareable project step. The AI is instructed that the roadmap fails validation if any module lacks a project. Examples: "Build a load-balanced web app with Terraform" or "Create a CI/CD pipeline for a microservices app." This ensures the user has proof of work to show employers, not just a list of topics they "learned."
SME Critique Loop (Career Paths)	After the AI generates a career roadmap, a second AI call is made—this time acting as a "Senior Engineer" or "Hiring Manager." This critique pass looks for: missing industry-standard tools, outdated technologies, unrealistic sequencing, weak explanations, and missing hands-on components. If high-severity issues are found, the roadmap is regenerated with the critique folded back into the prompt. Only the revised version is shown to the user. This catches hallucinations before the user sees them.
Dependency Risk Scoring + Conceptual Bridges	When the AI links two steps with a depends_on relationship, it also assigns a risk_score from 1 to 5. This score measures the conceptual leap between the two steps. If the score is 4 or higher (e.g., going from "JavaScript basics" to "Async/await patterns"), the system automatically generates a "Bridge Step"—a short, 5-minute checkpoint that explicitly translates the previous concept into the new context. This turns a steep cliff into a gentle ramp, directly applying Vygotsky's scaffolding theory to the graph structure.
Split Structure vs. Resources	The primary AI call generates only the step structure—text, kind, weight, dependsOn, and rationale. Resources (videos, articles, documentation) are generated in a separate, asynchronous batch call after the user accepts the steps. This means the user sees the structured roadmap 50% faster (shorter prompts = faster responses). If resource discovery fails or times out, the roadmap still exists—the user just sees "Resources pending..." and can start working on the steps immediately.
Retroactive Alignment (Tech-Stack Adjustment)	When a user completes a project step, the system runs a quick AI pass to detect the actual technologies they used (e.g., they built the project in Python instead of the roadmap's assumed Rust). The AI then generates a "migration patch"—a set of updated step texts and dependency changes for all future modules, switching the context to match what the user actually built. This patch is shown to the user for confirmation before being applied. The roadmap adapts to the learner's reality, not the other way around.
3. AI Provider & Prompt Layer
Suggestion	Detailed Description
Task-Aware Intelligent Routing	Every AI call is classified into a Tier. Tier 1 tasks (Voice acks, Verification checks, Clarifying questions) are fast, low-token, and high-frequency—they go to Groq or Cerebras. Tier 2 tasks (Assessment, Breakdown, Reformulation) are moderate complexity—they go to Gemini Flash. Tier 3 tasks (Outline generation, Career path generation, Self-critique) are heavy, high-reasoning—they go to Gemini Pro or NVIDIA. This preserves the fast/free quota for quick interactions and only accepts the 90-second NVIDIA latency for tasks that genuinely need a massive model.
Semantic Prompt Caching	The result of the Outline call is cached in memory using Caffeine, keyed by a hash of (Goal + Clarifications + ProfileSummary + GroundingHighlights). If the user regenerates the same goal twice (common during testing), the second call returns instantly from the cache. This saves daily quota for unique, genuine calls and speeds up repeated requests. The cache expires after 1 hour and has a maximum size of 1,000 entries.
Context Window Pruning	Instead of feeding the full raw profile and 10 search results into every prompt, the system prunes aggressively. The profile is reduced to a "Profile Diff" specific to the module being generated (e.g., only mention the user's Rust experience if the module is about Rust). Grounding results are filtered to the top 3 most relevant snippets based on keyword overlap with the step text. Smaller prompts = faster parsing = quicker Time-To-First-Token (TTFT). For NVIDIA's slow free tier, shaving 2,000 tokens can cut 15-20 seconds off the response time.
Dynamic Persona Switching	The AI is not a single, static expert. Based on the roadmap's archetype, domain, and the current phase, the system selects a specific persona and injects it into the system prompt. For a DevOps career path, the AI becomes a "Senior DevOps Engineer"—technical, pragmatic, automation-first. For a language-learning roadmap, the AI becomes a "Language Acquisition Expert"—encouraging, culturally aware, focused on comprehensible input. For a certification prep, the AI becomes an "Exam Strategist"—efficient, domain-aligned, focused on passing the test. This transforms the AI from a generic text generator into an authentic expert in the relevant field.
4. Provider Portfolio
Provider	Detailed Role Description
Groq	Tier 1 Primary. Used for all fast, high-frequency tasks: Voice acknowledgments, verification checks, clarifying questions, and resource searches. Its free tier offers 30 RPM and ~14,400 RPD, with output speeds around 500–700 tokens/second—about 10x faster than standard GPU APIs. Its 131K context window handles most prompts comfortably. Best for tasks where speed directly impacts UX.
Cerebras	Tier 1 Backup. A drop-in replacement for Groq with the same speed tier but a separate quota pool. Its free tier matches Groq's 30 RPM / ~14,400 RPD, but the context window is currently limited to 8K tokens on the free plan. Use it only for short prompts where the context limit isn't an issue.
Gemini Flash	Tier 2 Primary. Used for balanced, moderate-reasoning tasks: Assessment, Breakdown, Reformulation, and Idea Clustering. Its free tier offers 1,500 requests per day and a massive 1M token context window. This balances speed with deep reasoning and handles the full profile + grounding context without pruning.
Gemini Pro	Tier 3 Primary. Reserved for the most critical, complex tasks: Outline generation, Career path generation, and Self-critique. Its free tier is more limited (50 RPD) but offers the deepest reasoning capabilities. Only called when the task genuinely requires it.
DeepSeek	Tier 2/3 Backup. Accessed via OpenRouter's free tier. High-quality reasoning with generous daily limits (20 RPM, ~200 RPD depending on model). An excellent fallback when both Gemini Flash and Pro are exhausted, or when you need a different reasoning style.
NVIDIA NIM	Tier 3 Tertiary. The last-resort fallback. Offers 80+ models including DeepSeek, Qwen3 Coder, and Llama 4 Maverick. No per-token cost, but latency is high due to shared/queued GPU infrastructure. Use only when every other provider is exhausted. The free tier provides ~5,000 total credits with a 12-month expiry.
5. Pedagogical Rigor
Principle	Detailed Enhancement Description
Spaced Repetition	Already implemented in Phase 8. The system re-checks completed steps at increasing intervals (days → weeks). This is the most evidence-backed learning technique for long-term retention. Continue using the resurfacing engine exactly as designed.
Desirable Difficulties	Already implemented via verification checks. Enhancement: Add an optional "confidence check" after verification—ask the user "How confident are you in this answer?" This engages metacognition and helps the system calibrate future re-check intervals.
Scaffolding / ZPD	Already implemented via Outline → Expand. Enhancement: Add "Conceptual Bridges" for high-risk dependencies (see above). This is a direct application of Vygotsky's Zone of Proximal Development—providing just-in-time support to bridge the gap between what the user knows and what they're about to learn.
Interleaving	Currently not implemented. Enhancement: In the Learning Path view, mix practice across modules instead of strict blocking. For example, if the user is in Module 3, occasionally suggest a review question from Module 1. This strengthens connections and reduces forgetting.
Retrieval Practice	Already implemented via verification. Enhancement: Add light checks between steps, not just at completion. For example, after Step 1.2, a quick "What was the key concept from Step 1.1?" This forces the user to actively recall, strengthening memory.
Transfer	Currently implicit via project steps. Enhancement: Explicitly prompt the AI to design steps that require applying knowledge in a new context, not just repeating the tutorial. Example: "Build a weather app" → "Build a stock tracker using the same patterns but with a different API." This promotes transfer—the ability to apply knowledge in novel situations.
Personalization	Already implemented via Profile. Enhancement: Enforce explicit transparency. The AI must state: "Skipping X because your profile says Y." If the user disagrees, they can override. This builds trust and gives the user agency over their learning path.
