7. Double-Check Pass (AI Reviewer)
Suggestion	Detailed Description
Lightweight Check	Runs on Groq (fast, cheap). Checks for obvious issues: steps out of order, unclear descriptions, missing prerequisites, inconsistent formatting. This catches surface-level problems quickly without burning expensive quota.
Heavy Check	Runs on Gemini Pro (deeper reasoning). Checks for: technical accuracy, industry alignment (are the tools still relevant?), structural issues (does the sequence make sense?), completeness (are there gaps?). This is the "Senior Engineer" review.
Trigger Conditions	Runs automatically after: module expansion (check the new steps), substep breakdown (check the breakdown), and before showing the final outline (catch issues early).
Skip Conditions	Skip if: the roadmap is flat and has fewer than 5 steps (too simple to bother), the user has already edited the steps (they're curating, so trust them), the check already ran within 24 hours (don't repeat unnecessarily), or provider quota is low (preserve it for more important tasks).
UI Display	Issues are displayed with severity levels: HIGH (must fix), MEDIUM (should fix), LOW (nice-to-fix). Each issue has an "Accept suggestion" button (applies the fix automatically) and a "Dismiss" button (the user disagrees). This gives the user full control while benefiting from the AI's review.
8. On-Demand Testing System
Suggestion	Detailed Description
QCM (Multiple Choice)	Auto-evaluated. The AI generates a question with 4 options and marks the correct one. The user selects an answer and gets instant feedback with an explanation. Fast, low-cost, and great for conceptual steps.
Code Challenge	AI-evaluated. The AI provides a coding problem with starter code and a description. The user writes code in a text area. The AI evaluates the code against test cases and provides feedback (pass/fail + gap analysis). This takes 3-5 seconds of AI time.
Scenario-Based	AI-evaluated. The AI provides a realistic scenario and asks "What would you do?" The user writes a free-text answer. The AI evaluates against key points and provides feedback. Great for practical/design steps.
Format Detection	The system auto-detects the best format based on step content. If the step contains "build," "implement," or "code," it defaults to Code Challenge. If it contains "design" or "architect," it defaults to Scenario-Based. Otherwise, it uses QCM. The user can override this with their own preference.
Test Generation	When the user clicks "Take Test," the AI generates the test immediately (2-5 seconds). The test is tailored to the step's content, difficulty level, and the user's profile (beginner → simpler questions, advanced → harder questions).
Feedback	If the user answers incorrectly, the system shows: the correct answer (for QCM), a gap analysis (what they missed), and a resource recommendation (where to review). This turns failure into a learning opportunity.
User Control	The user can choose their preferred format (QCM/Code/Scenario) or select "Auto" and let the system decide. They can also skip testing entirely—it's always optional.
9. Proactive Nudges (The "Nudge" System)
Trigger	Detailed Suggestion Description
Module completion	When the user marks the final step of a module as "done," show: "Great work! You've completed the 'Advanced Networking' module. Before moving to the next module, consider adding a practice lab to reinforce what you've learned. [Add practice lab] [Skip]".
Near roadmap completion	When the user reaches 80%+ progress on a career path, show: "You're almost done with your DevOps Engineer roadmap! Most successful career changers add a capstone project to showcase their skills. Want to add one? [Add capstone project] [Skip for now]".
Fast completion	When the user completes a step in less than 50% of the estimated time, show: "You finished this step much faster than expected! If you're feeling confident, we can suggest some deeper resources to explore. [Find deeper resources] [Skip]".
Slow completion	When the user takes more than 200% of the estimated time, show: "This step took longer than expected. It might be worth reviewing a prerequisite or getting extra help. Want to review prerequisites? [Review prerequisites] [Skip]".
Career path near end	When the user is at 90%+ progress on a career path, show: "You're nearly ready to start applying! Most engineers in this field also learn [adjacent topic]. Want to add a short module on it? [Add module] [Skip]".
Guardrails (prevent overwhelm):

Cooldown: No nudges within 5 minutes of the last nudge—prevents spamming.

Max per session: Maximum 3 nudges per user session—keeps it helpful, not annoying.

Skip tracking: If the user skips a nudge type 3 times, stop suggesting that type—respects their preference.

Quota-aware: Skip nudges entirely if AI provider quota is low—preserve it for essential tasks.

Context relevance: Only show nudges when progress ≥ 70%—don't nudge at the beginning.

