14. Retroactive Alignment (Tech-Stack Adjustment)
Suggestion	Detailed Description
Tech Detection	When a user completes a project step, the system extracts the step's text and the user's session notes/comments. A quick AI pass analyzes: "Given this step and the user's notes, what specific technologies did they actually use?"
Migration Patch	If the detected technology differs from the roadmap's assumption (e.g., the roadmap assumed Rust, but the user built it in Python), the AI generates a patch. This patch contains updated step texts for all future modules, rewritten to use the user's actual tech stack. Dependencies are also updated (e.g., "Learn Python frameworks" instead of "Learn Rust crates").
User Confirmation	The patch is shown to the user as a "proposal" before being applied. The user sees: "You built this project in Python. Should we update the remaining steps to match?" They can accept, reject, or edit the proposed changes. This maintains user agency.
Impact	The roadmap adapts to the learner's reality. If the user deliberately chose Python over Rust, the rest of the roadmap follows their decision. This prevents a common frustration—being forced to learn a technology you don't want to use.
15. Dynamic Re-Forecasting (Pacing)
Suggestion	Detailed Description
Pace Detection	The system tracks the user's actual session durations across all steps. It calculates: average actual minutes per step vs. average estimated minutes per step. This yields a paceMultiplier.
Down-Scope	If the user is moving 2x slower than predicted (paceMultiplier > 2.0), the system suggests trimming the remaining unexpanded modules. It calculates: "At your current pace, this roadmap will take 8 months instead of 4. We can cut Module 5 (Advanced) and replace it with a single 'Bridge to Production' step."
Add Depth	If the user is moving 2x faster than predicted (paceMultiplier < 0.5), the system suggests adding depth: "You're flying through this! Want to add 2 more advanced steps to each remaining module?"
User Confirmation	The recommendation is shown to the user as a modal: "Pacing Adjustment: We noticed you're [slower/faster] than expected. Here's our suggestion. [Accept] [Reject] [Edit]." This keeps the user in control.
Benefit	Prevents abandonment. A user who feels "behind" gets a realistic plan. A user who feels "ahead" gets more depth. The roadmap adapts to the learner's real-life pace, not the AI's ideal.
